summary: Introduced the SBIR Website Improvement Act to make the SBIR and STTR award database searchable by research institutions and to identify and collect data on Minority Serving Institutions (MSIs), encouraging partnerships between small businesses and academic/research institutions and supporting diverse participation in federally funded R&D and technology transfer efforts. Also supported early learning programs and measures to expand access to affordable child care, including the Expanding Child Care Access Act which creates supports for family (in-home) child care providers to increase availability of quality, affordable options for families. Secured community project funding for The Learning Commons: Space for Learning, Meeting and Collaboration and improvements to a free public library to expand community learning spaces and resources. Announced senior staff with direct higher education and education-policy experience (Laney O’Shea worked on education issues; Seth Levin served as Legislative Liaison at the NJ Office of the Secretary of Higher Education), reinforcing attention to education and higher-education partnerships in the office's legislative portfolio.

Gill convened a 12-member 2025 Service Academy Board to comprehensively screen and interview high school and college applicants for congressional nominations to the U.S. service academies (West Point, Naval Academy, Air Force Academy, Merchant Marine Academy). He emphasized a rigorous selection process and working with former military, education, and community leaders to recommend qualified young people from TX-26 for academy appointments and eventual service in the U.S. Armed Forces. He also announced the 2025 Congressional App Challenge winner from TX-26, praising STEM and computer science education, celebrating student innovation in app development, and supporting opportunities (like the #HouseOfCode reception) that promote computer science careers for district students. In January 2026 he introduced the Student Visa Integrity Act to tighten oversight of foreign students, expand in-person interview requirements, restrict program transfers, require schools to disclose financial or institutional ties to the Chinese government, establish firm program end dates to prevent overstays, and bar nationals of designated 'adversarial' countries from studying in the United States—framing these measures as protecting campuses and American institutions from exploitation. He also hosts and promotes the annual Congressional Art Competition in TX-26, inviting public, private, and home-schooled high school students to submit original artwork, highlighting student creativity and arts education in the district, and arranging for winning pieces to be displayed in the U.S. Capitol and district offices. Additionally, in May 2025 he co-introduced the Foreign Influence Transparency and Accountability Act with Sen. Ted Cruz to penalize universities that accept funds from designated adversarial countries and fail to disclose foreign gifts as required under the Higher Education Act. That legislation would impose large excise taxes on funds from countries of concern (300%), heavy penalties for unreported funds (110%), and mandate biennial audits of 30 institutions (prioritizing large endowments and past misconduct), reflecting his view that foreign funding can compromise academic integrity, student formation, and research and should be subject to strict transparency and accountability.

Introduced/supports the Right to Read Act to boost student literacy by expanding access to school libraries and certified librarians, funding evidence-based reading instruction, stocking diverse reading materials, supporting family literacy programs, addressing post-pandemic declines in reading scores, and countering book bans that limit student learning. As a longtime school board member and former county supervisor, champions reversing attacks on public education and securing robust investments in schools, educators, and students; has led efforts to expand early childhood access and local education initiatives. Also supports protecting Native languages and ensuring federal education policy reflects the needs of Indian Country through meaningful tribal consultation. Recently cosponsored additional education measures including College For All, Arts Education for All, Expanding Mental Health Services Access in Schools, Department of Education Protection Act, and other bills to expand access, mental-health supports, and protections for federal education institutions.

Prioritizes career and technical education (CTE) and local workforce training. Welcomed U.S. Secretary of Education Linda McMahon to tour the Central Educational Center in Newnan, highlighted the public-private partnership (Newnan-Coweta Chamber, Coweta County School System, West Georgia Technical College) that created the model, convened a bipartisan roundtable on Presidential and Congressional education and workforce development initiatives, and showcased CTE labs (Precision Machining, Dental Assisting, Aviation, Audio Production) where students demonstrated job-ready skills. Noted the State of Georgia has invested over $200 million to replicate the Central Educational Center model across 50 counties—underscoring his focus on expanding technical training in high school to prepare students for modern jobs.
